          'Introduction: The Indian Constitution, drafted by the Constituent Assembly under Dr. B.R. Ambedkar, came into force on 26 January 1950.\nFeatures:\n1. Lengthiest written constitution - originally 395 articles, 22 parts, 8 schedules.\n2. Drawn from many sources: Parliamentary system (UK), Fundamental Rights (USA), Directive Principles (Ireland), federalism (Canada), emergency (Germany).\n3. Preamble: declares India a Sovereign Socialist Secular Democratic Republic ensuring justice, liberty, equality and fraternity.\n4. Federal with unitary bias: division of powers (Union, State, Concurrent lists) but strong centre in emergencies.\n5. Parliamentary democracy: real executive (PM & Council) responsible to Lok Sabha; nominal head - President.\n6. Fundamental Rights justiciable; Fundamental Duties; Directive Principles.\n7. Independent judiciary with judicial review.\n8. Universal adult franchise, single citizenship, integrated bureaucracy (IAS/IPS).\n9. Rigid and flexible amendment procedure (Article 368).\nConclusion: It is a living document that balances rigidity with flexibility, making India the world\'s largest democracy.'),
      QA('Describe the powers and functions of the President of India / Prime Minister.',
          'President (nominal executive):\n1. Executive powers - all executive actions taken in the President\'s name; appoints PM, ministers, Governors, judges, CAG, EC.\n2. Legislative powers - summons & dissolves Lok Sabha; gives assent to bills; issues ordinances (Article 123) when Parliament is not in session.\n3. Financial powers - money bills introduced with prior recommendation; Contingency Fund.\n4. Judicial powers - pardoning power (Article 72): pardon, reprieve, respite, remit, commute.\n5. Emergency powers - National (352), State (356), Financial (360).\nPrime Minister (real executive):\n1. Head of the Council of Ministers - allocates portfolios, presides over cabinet meetings.\n2. Link between President and the cabinet.\n3. Leader of the Lok Sabha & leader of the majority party - guides and coordinates policy.\n4. Chief spokesperson of the government in Parliament and nation.\nConclusion: Under our parliamentary system the President reigns but does not rule; real power lies with the PM and Council of Ministers.'),
      QA('Explain the composition and functions of the Indian Parliament.',
          'Introduction: Parliament consists of the President and two Houses - Lok Sabha and Rajya Sabha.\nLok Sabha (max 550): directly elected from territorial constituencies; 5-year term; money bills only here; controls ministry through no-confidence motion.\nRajya Sabha (max 250): 238 elected by State/UT assemblies by proportional representation + 12 nominated by the President (art, literature, science, social service); permanent body, members 6-year term, one-third retire every 2 years.\nFunctions:\n1. Legislative - makes laws on Union & Concurrent list through three readings and presidential assent.\n2. Financial - passes budget; Lok Sabha controls money bills and taxation; no tax without authority of law.\n3. Executive control - question hour, adjournment motions, no-confidence motion.\n4. Constitutional amendment (Article 368).\n5. Electoral - participates in election of President & Vice-President; impeachment of President and judges.\n6. Deliberative - discusses matters of public importance.\nConclusion: Parliament is the temple of democracy reflecting the sovereign will of the people.'),
      QA('Explain the features of the Indian Judiciary.',
          'Introduction: India has a single integrated judicial system with the Supreme Court at the top.\nFeatures:\n1. Independence of judiciary - separated from executive; security of tenure of judges; salaries charged on Consolidated Fund; power to punish for contempt.\n2. Supreme Court (Article 124): Chief Justice + judges appointed by the President (collegium). Jurisdictions: original (centre-state disputes), appellate (civil/criminal/constitutional appeals), advisory (Article 143), court of record.\n3. High Courts at state level; subordinate/district courts below.\n4. Judicial review - can strike down unconstitutional laws; guardian of Fundamental Rights (writs: Habeas Corpus, Mandamus, Prohibition, Certiorari, Quo Warranto).\n5. Public Interest Litigation (PIL) - justice to the poor.\n6. Single citizenship & common civil law of the land.\nConclusion: An independent, impartial and integrated judiciary protects the Constitution and the rights of citizens.'),
    ],
    mcqs: const [
      MCQ('The Constitution of India came into force on',
          ['15 August 1947', '26 November 1949', '26 January 1950', '2 October 1950'],
          2, '26 January 1950 - celebrated as Republic Day.'),
      MCQ('The word "Secular" was added to the Preamble by which amendment?',
          ['1st', '24th', '42nd', '73rd'],
          2, 'The 42nd Amendment (1976) added Socialist, Secular and Integrity.'),
      MCQ('Right to Constitutional Remedies is in Article',
          ['14', '19', '21', '32'],
          3, 'Article 32 - the "heart and soul" (Ambedkar); writs can be issued.'),
      MCQ('The real executive head of the Union is',
          ['President', 'Vice-President', 'Prime Minister', 'Chief Justice'],
          2, 'The PM and Council of Ministers exercise real power.'),
      MCQ('Rajya Sabha members have a term of',
          ['4 years', '5 years', '6 years', 'Life'],
          2, '6 years; one-third retire every 2 years.'),
      MCQ('Money Bills can be introduced only in the',
          ['Rajya Sabha', 'Lok Sabha', 'Either house', 'State Assembly'],
          1, 'Money bills originate only in Lok Sabha (Article 110).'),
      MCQ('The 73rd Constitutional Amendment deals with',
          ['Municipalities', 'Panchayati Raj', 'Fundamental Duties', 'GST'],
          1, '73rd - Panchayats (rural); 74th - Municipalities (urban).'),
      MCQ('Elections in India are conducted by',
          ['Supreme Court', 'Parliament', 'Election Commission of India', 'President'],
          2, 'Article 324 vests this power in the ECI.'),
    ],
  ),

