    shortAnswers: const [
      QA('Define Depreciation. State its causes.',
          'Depreciation is the gradual and permanent decrease in the value of a fixed asset due to wear and tear, passage of time or obsolescence. Causes: constant use, effluxion of time, obsolescence (technology change), accidents, depletion (mines).'),
      QA('Distinguish between Provision and Reserve.',
          'Provision is a charge against profits for a known liability or expected loss (e.g., provision for doubtful debts) - it must be made whether there is profit or loss. Reserve is an appropriation of profits made to strengthen the financial position (general reserve) - it is created only out of profits.'),
      QA('What is a Bill of Exchange?',
          'A bill of exchange is an instrument in writing, an unconditional order signed by the maker (drawer), directing a certain person (drawee) to pay a certain sum of money only to the bearer or order of a certain person (payee). It must be accepted by the drawee to become valid.'),
      QA('Distinguish between Bill of Exchange and Promissory Note.',
          'Bill of exchange: an order to pay, drawn by the creditor; needs acceptance; has three parties (drawer, drawee, payee). Promissory note: a promise to pay, made by the debtor; no acceptance needed; has two parties (maker, payee).'),
      QA('What is Consignment?',
          'Consignment is the sending of goods by the owner (consignor) to his agent (consignee) in another place for sale on his behalf and risk, for a commission. Ownership of goods remains with the consignor until they are sold.'),
      QA('What is Del Credere Commission?',
          'Del credere commission is the extra commission paid to the consignee when he undertakes the risk of bad debts - if the consignee guarantees collection of all credit sales. Bad debts loss is then borne by the consignee, not the consignor.'),
      QA('State the features of a Joint Venture.',
          '1. It is a temporary partnership formed for a particular project/venture. 2. No separate firm name is needed. 3. Co-venturers contribute capital and share profits/losses in an agreed ratio. 4. The venture ends automatically when the project is completed.'),
      QA('Distinguish between Receipts & Payments A/c and Income & Expenditure A/c.',
          'Receipts & Payments Account is a real account - a summary of all cash receipts and payments (capital + revenue, any year). Income & Expenditure Account is a nominal account showing only revenue items of the current year to find surplus or deficit (like a P&L account for non-profit organisations).'),
      QA('What is a Partnership Deed?',
          'Partnership deed is the written agreement between partners containing terms such as name of firm, capital contribution, profit-sharing ratio, interest on capital/drawings, salary to partners, admission/retirement terms and dispute settlement. In its absence, the Partnership Act 1932 rules apply (equal profits, no interest on capital).'),
      QA('Distinguish between Shares and Debentures.',
          'Shares: owned capital; holders are members/owners; dividend paid out of profits (no fixed rate for equity); not redeemable (equity) during company\'s life. Debentures: borrowed capital; holders are creditors; fixed interest payable regardless of profits; redeemable after a fixed period.'),
    ],
    essays: const [
      QA('Explain the Straight Line and Written Down Value methods of depreciation with examples.',
          'Introduction: Depreciation allocates the cost of a fixed asset over its useful life.\n1. Straight Line Method (Fixed Instalment Method): a fixed, equal amount is charged every year.\nFormula: Depreciation = (Cost of Asset - Scrap Value) / Estimated Life.\nExample: Cost Rs.1,10,000, scrap value Rs.10,000, life 10 years -> annual depreciation = Rs.10,000 every year. Merits: simple, asset value becomes zero at the end. Limitation: repairs rise in later years, so total charge is unequal.\n2. Written Down Value Method (Diminishing Balance Method): fixed percentage is charged on the reducing book value each year. Depreciation is heavy in early years and light later, matching heavy repairs later - total charge roughly equal every year.\nExample: asset Rs.1,00,000 @ 10% -> Yr1: 10,000 (WDV 90,000), Yr2: 9,000 (WDV 81,000).\nJournal entry (both methods): Depreciation A/c Dr. To Asset A/c; P&L A/c Dr. To Depreciation A/c.\nConclusion: SLM suits leases/patents; WDV suits machinery and is accepted for income tax in India.'),
      QA('Explain the important terms and accounting treatment of Bills of Exchange.',
          'Introduction: A bill of exchange is a negotiable instrument used in credit transactions (Negotiable Instruments Act, 1881).\nTerms:\n1. Drawer - maker/creditor; Drawee - debtor on whom drawn; Payee - receiver of money.\n2. Acceptance - drawee signs assent; bill becomes legally valid.\n3. Tenure & Maturity - time of payment; add 3 days of grace to find maturity date.\n4. Discounting of bill - bill encashed at bank before maturity; bank charges discounting charges (interest).\n5. Endorsement - transfer of the bill to another person by signing on the back.\n6. Dishonour - non-payment at maturity; Noting charges - fees paid to notary public for recording dishonour, ultimately recovered from drawee.\n7. Retiring the bill (payment before due date with rebate) and Renewal (old bill cancelled, new bill with interest).\nAccounting entries: In books of drawer: Bills Receivable A/c Dr. to Drawee; on discounting: Bank A/c Dr., Discounting Charges A/c Dr. to B/R A/c.\nConclusion: Bills of exchange facilitate credit sales and provide legal evidence of debt.'),
      QA('Explain the accounts prepared in Consignment and their journal entries.',
          'Introduction: On consignment the consignor records transactions in three accounts.\n1. Consignment Account (nominal account): debited with cost of goods sent, consignor\'s expenses (freight, insurance), consignee\'s expenses (carriage, godown rent) and consignee\'s commission; credited with sales made by consignee. Balance = profit or loss on consignment, transferred to General P&L A/c.\n2. Consignee\'s (Personal) Account: debited with sales (cash & credit), credited with his expenses, commission and remittances; balance shows amount due from consignee.\n3. Goods Sent on Consignment Account: credited with cost of goods sent; transferred to Trading Account.\nSpecial items: Stock on consignment valued at cost or net realisable value whichever is lower (plus proportionate non-recurring expenses); Normal loss ignored (cost absorbed by good units); Abnormal loss valued and transferred to P&L; Del credere commission covers bad debts.\nKey entries: Goods sent: Consignment A/c Dr. to Goods sent on consignment. Expenses of consignee: Consignment A/c Dr. to Consignee. Sales: Consignee A/c Dr. to Consignment. Commission: Consignment A/c Dr. to Consignee.\nConclusion: These accounts reveal consignment profit and the consignee\'s liability.'),
      QA('Explain the accounts of Non-Profit (Not-for-Profit) Organisations.',
          'Introduction: Clubs, societies, schools and hospitals rendering service without profit motive maintain simple records.\n1. Receipts and Payments Account: opens with cash/bank balance; records all cash receipts and payments (capital + revenue, relating to any year); closes with cash/bank balance. It is a summary of the cash book.\n2. Income and Expenditure Account: like a P&L A/c - only revenue items of the current year (accrual basis): credit subscriptions (current year), donations for general purpose, interest; debit salaries, rent, printing. Balance = Surplus (excess of income) or Deficit - transferred to Capital Fund in the Balance Sheet.\n3. Balance Sheet: shows accumulated/capital fund (opening balance + surplus), specific funds (tournament fund), liabilities and assets.\nSpecial treatments: Life membership fees & specific donations -> capitalised (Balance Sheet liability); entrance fees (if non-recurring) capitalised; sale of old newspapers, sports material treated by nature; outstanding subscription added to subscription and shown as asset.\nConclusion: These statements show whether the organisation lives within its income.'),
    ],
    mcqs: const [
