    essays: const [
      QA('Write an essay on "Digital India - Opportunities and Challenges".',
          'Introduction: Digital India is the dream of transforming India into a digitally empowered society and knowledge economy.\nOpportunities:\n1. e-Governance - certificates, pensions and services at fingertips (T-App Folio in Telangana).\n2. Digital payments (UPI) - transparent, cashless economy.\n3. Online education and skill development beyond classrooms.\n4. Employment in IT and startups (T-Hub); work-from-home culture.\n5. Telemedicine reaching remote villages.\nChallenges:\n1. Digital divide between urban and rural India.\n2. Cyber security threats, online frauds and data privacy.\n3. Digital illiteracy among elders and the poor.\n4. Misinformation on social media.\nConclusion: With digital literacy, strong cyber security and inclusive infrastructure, Digital India can empower every citizen. The youth must use technology as a tool, not be used by it.'),
      QA('Write a report for a newspaper on "Inter Collegiate Science Fair organised in your college".',
          'Format and model:\nHeadline: Science Fair Sparks Young Minds at Govt Junior College\nByline: By a Staff Reporter\nPlace-Date: Hyderabad, 15 July 2026\n\nPara 1 (What, where, when): A one-day Inter-Collegiate Science Fair was organised at Government Junior College, Hyderabad on 14 July 2026. Twelve colleges from the city participated.\nPara 2 (Details): Students displayed 60 exhibits on renewable energy, robotics and water conservation. The District Collector, the chief guest, appreciated the working model of a solar water purifier made by the college\'s second-year students.\nPara 3 (Prizes/quote): "Innovation must solve local problems," the Collector said. Prizes were distributed to the best three exhibits; XYZ College bagged the overall championship trophy.\nPara 4 (Conclusion): The fair ended with a vote of thanks by the Principal, who announced that it would be held every year.\nTips: past tense, third person, factual, 150-200 words, no personal opinion.'),
      QA('Explain the art of writing a good essay for board exams.',
          'Introduction: An essay tests ideas, organisation and language together.\nSteps:\n1. Understand the topic; brainstorm points quickly in the margin.\n2. Structure: Introduction (definition/quote/hook) -> 4-5 Body paragraphs (one idea each with examples) -> Conclusion (summary, suggestion, call to action).\n3. Use linking words: firstly, moreover, however, on the other hand, in addition, finally, to conclude.\n4. Write simple, correct sentences; avoid slang and SMS language.\n5. Add value: a proverb, a scheme name (e.g., Haritha Haram), a statistic if sure.\n6. Watch: handwriting, paragraphing, word limit, and leave 3 minutes to re-read and correct errors.\nCommon mistakes to avoid: repeating the same idea, going off-topic, wrong tense sequence, memorised but irrelevant content.\nConclusion: Practice one essay a week and get it evaluated - improvement comes from feedback.'),
      QA('Write an essay on "Role of Youth in Nation Building".',
          'Introduction: Youth are the greatest wealth and the strongest power of any nation; India has the largest youth population in the world.\nBody:\n1. Agents of change: fresh ideas, innovation and entrepreneurship (startups, T-Hub).\n2. Education & skill: today\'s student is tomorrow\'s professional, scientist, farmer-entrepreneur.\n3. Social responsibility: fighting corruption, casteism and superstition; blood donation, cleanliness drives, voter awareness.\n4. Protecting democracy: informed voting and respecting the Constitution.\n5. Balance: use technology wisely; avoid addictions; respect parents and teachers.\nExamples: Bhagat Singh and Swami Vivekananda inspired youth; today ISRO\'s young scientists make India proud.\nConclusion: As Dr. A.P.J. Abdul Kalam said, dreams transform into thoughts and thoughts into action. Disciplined, skilled and patriotic youth will make India a developed nation by 2047.'),
    ],
    mcqs: const [
      MCQ('Choose the correct question tag: "You are coming tomorrow, ___?"',
